{{Infobox court case | name = BONZ Group (Pty) Ltd v Cooke | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = | full name = BONZ Group (Pty) Ltd v Diane Leone Cooke | citations = [1994] 3 NZLR 216 | judges = | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = [http://www.nzlii.org/nz/cases/NZHC/1994/1004.pdf High Court judgment] | Keywords = }}
'''BONZ Group (Pty) Ltd v Cooke''' [1994] 3 NZLR 216 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding section 9 of the [[Fair Trading Act 1986]].
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Court of Appeal of New Zealand cases]] [[Category:1994 in New Zealand law]] [[Category:1994 in case law]]
{{NewZealand-case-law-stub}}

[[File:Building 64, Alcatraz.jpg|thumb|Building 64]] '''Building 64''', also known as the '''64 Building''', '''Building #64''' or the '''Building 64 Residential Apartments''', was the first building constructed on the island of [[Alcatraz]] off the coast of [[San Francisco]], USA, entirely for the purpose of accommodating the military officers and their families living on the island.<ref name="Jr2011">{{cite book|last=Jr|first=Jerry Lewis Champion|title=The Fading Voices of Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxH3-mB5rCcC&pg=PA91|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=27 January 2011|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4567-1488-8|page=91}}</ref> Located next to the [[Alcatraz Wharf|dock]] on the southeastern side of the island below the [[Warden's House (Alcatraz Island)|Warden's House]],<ref name="MacDonaldNadel2012">{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Donald|last2=Nadel|first2=Ira|title=Alcatraz: History and Design of a Landmark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wfQWSJLKXdoC&pg=PA13|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=15 February 2012|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-1-4521-0153-8|page=13}}</ref> the three-story apartment block was built in 1905 on the site of a U.S. Army barracks which had been there from the 1860s. It functioned as the Military Guard Barracks from 1906 until 1933. One of its largest apartments in the southwest corner was known as the "Cow Palace" and a nearby alleyway was known as "Chinatown".<ref name="Jr2011"/>
During Federal prison times from 1934, the building gradually fell into a shabby state, and new quarters were built on the Parade Grounds, but most families arriving on the island stayed in Building 64 until a room in the newer quarters was available.<ref name="Dunbar1999">{{cite book|last=Dunbar|first=Richard|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoXM5O9glN8C&pg=PA71|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Casa Editrice Bonechi|isbn=978-88-8029-940-0|page=71}}</ref> Most of the other residential quarters have since been demolished, but Building 64 remains and has since been renovated.<ref name="Wellman2008">{{cite book|last=Wellman|first=Gregory L.|title=A History of Alcatraz Island:: 1853-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1duAUPaHSgcC&pg=PA118|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=28 May 2008|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-5815-8|page=118}}</ref> During the [[Occupation of Alcatraz]], in 1970 the Native Americans drew graffiti in red around the "United States Penitentiary" sign saying "Indians welcome" and "Indian land". There is a book store on the ground floor on the left side of the building.
==Gallery== <gallery> File:Alcatraz wharf2.jpg|Alcatraz wharf and Building 64 File:Alcatraz Island 03.jpg|Building 64 is the large pillared building on the lower left File:Alcatraz Island - panoramio (3).jpg|Prison sign on building and the Indian graffiti File:Alcatraz aerial.jpg|The 64 building can be seen furthest to the top left </gallery>
