'''''Uralsky Sovremennik''''' ({{lang-rus|Уральский современник}}, lit. "contemporary Ural"), later known as simply '''''Ural''''' ({{lang-rus|Урал}}), was a literary [[almanac]] published in the [[Soviet Union]] from 1938 to 1957. The magazine was based in [[Yekaterinburg|Sverdlovsk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alib.ru/5_uralnmnskij_sovremennik_alnmnmanah_sverdlovskogo_otdeleniya_soyuza_pisatelej_sssr_n3_33_w1t702c3664e009d091c765c75af598ac947fe.html|title=Уральский современник. Альманах свердловского отделения союза писателей СССР N3 (33). Краеведение России: Сибирь, Дальний Восток |publisher=Alib.ru|language=Russian|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref> It mostly published the works of the authors from the [[Ural (region)|Ural region]].<ref name="belinsky">{{cite web|url=http://book.uraic.ru/events/2008/01/0/533|title=Памятная дата из истории края|date=January 2008|work=Calendar of events|publisher=Sverdlovsk Regional Research Library of V. G. Belinsky|language=Russian|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref> The almanac was operated by the Sverdlovsk department of the [[Union of Soviet Writers]].<ref name="okryljajushhemu"/>
The almanac was founded as ''Uralsky Sovremennik'' in 1938 by [[Klavdiya Rozhdestvenskaya]], the [[editor-in-chief]] of the [[Sverdlovsk Publishing House]].<ref name="okryljajushhemu">{{cite journal|last=Rozhdestvenskaya|first=Yelena |year=2005|title=Moemu neizmenno okryljajushhemu redaktoru: vspominaja Pavla Petrovicha Bazhova |script-title = ru:Моему неизменно окрыляющему редактору: вспоминая Павла Петровича Бажова | trans-title =To my always inspiring editor: remembering Pavel Petrovich Bazhov|journal=Ural|location=Yekaterinburg |volume=1|url= http://magazines.russ.ru/ural/2005/1/r16.html|language=Russian}}</ref> It existed under that title until 1956, with 33 volumes released. Among editors of the almanac were Klavdiya Rozhdestvenskaya herself, the famous Ural writer [[Pavel Bazhov]], N. Popova, V. A. Starikov. Pavel Bazhov's fairy tales, such as "[[The Stone Flower]]", "[[The Malachite Casket (fairy tale)|The Malachite Casket]]", "[[Silver Hoof]]" , were published in it.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bazhov|first=Pavel|authorlink=Pavel Bazhov|editor=Valentina Bazhova |editor2=[[Alexey Surkov]] |editor3=Yevgeny Permyak|title=Sobranie sochinenij v trekh tomakh|trans-title= Works. In Three Volumes|script-title=ru:Собрание сочинений в трех томах|volume=1|year=1952|publisher=[[Khudozhestvennaya Literatura]]|location=Moscow|language=Russian|page=243}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://fantlab.ru/work87517 |title=Серебряное копытце |trans-title= Silver Hoof|publisher=[[FantLab]]|language=Russian|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>
During the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Great Patriotic War]] it published the works of the evacuated writers. After some debate the Union of Soviet Writers decided to reorganize the magazine to expand the number of authors and "its circle of topics".<ref name="belinsky"/> In 1957 a new editorial board was hired, ''Uralsky Sovremennik'' was renamed to ''Ural''. Only 4 volumes (1/34—4/37) were published under that title. It was shut down the same year.<ref name="belinsky"/>
